Pattern 2: Fast & Slow (Chasing / In-Place Modification)
1. The Interview Triggers
*. Requirements specifying In-Place manipulation with $O(1)$ space constraints.
* Separating, removing, or filtering array elements based on a dynamic criteria.
* Circular loop dependencies or cyclic generation (e.g., Linked List cycles or math variations).

2. Core Mechanics
Both pointers start moving from the same side of the array structure. The fast pointer iterates systematically through the whole array. The slow pointer acts as a persistent anchor or placeholder, advancing only when a distinct target condition evaluates to true.

3. Production Java Blueprint
public int fastSlowTemplate(int[] nums) {
    if (nums == null || nums.length == 0) return 0;
    
    int slow = 0; // Tracks the write-index location
    
    for (int fast = 0; fast < nums.length; fast++) {
        // Example Condition: Keep elements that meet your condition
        if (isValidElement(nums[fast])) {
            nums[slow] = nums[fast]; // Overwrite data in-place
            slow++; // Advance write-position
        }
    }
    return slow; // 'slow' usually denotes the new length of the modified array
}

4. Corner Cases & Interview Pitfalls
*. Lookbacks: If comparing elements backward (e.g., nums[fast] == nums[fast - 2]), verify the baseline limits (fast >= 2) explicitly to prevent a java.lang.ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException.

5. Essential Interview Questions
Easy: LeetCode 26 - Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array, LeetCode 283 - Move Zeroes
Medium: LeetCode 80 - Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array II, LeetCode 287 - Find the Duplicate Number
